node.text:
As the Pleiades star cluster rises, it signals the start of Matariki, the Māori New Year. Matariki is about celebrating the present and looking forward to the future while remembering the past. 'Kia whakatōmuri te haere whakamua' - I walk backwards into the future with my eyes fixed on my past. 

How would you make your Matariki special this year? #MatarikiMoment ✨

node.text:
Did you know that the Māori name for Franz Josef Glacier is Kā Roimata o Hinehukatere which means "The tears of Hinehukatere"? ❄️🏔️ ​

Local legend tells of the tragic love story of Hinehukatere and Wawe. Hinehukatere had a passion for mountaineering and took her sweetheart Wawe into the mountains with her. He tried to keep up but was not as agile and lost his footing, falling to his death. Hinehukatere was heartbroken and cried and cried. As a memorial to her sorrow, the gods (Atua) froze her tears into a giant river of ice, forming the glacier that we see today!​

 #NewZealand ​
📷: @roadynz

Can you spot the kākāpō? 🌳 🐦​

Duke can! Duke helps @docgovtnz with their work protecting kākāpō, the world's only flightless parrot. We might struggle to see kākāpō in the forest but Duke is specially trained to find them with his strong sense of smell. Duke spotted this kākāpō on Whenua Hou, a sanctuary island near Stewart Island / Rakiura.​
#InternationalDogDay #NewZealand
